			<span class="kicker"><a href="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/category/other-topics/markets/">Markets</a></span>		</div>
				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Volatility Hits European and Asian Stocks After Frenzy on Wall Street</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Mark Scott and Neil Gough			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2014-10-16T02:24:28+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">October 15, 2014 10:24 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">October 15, 2014 10:24 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content">
	<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="https://dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/10/15/stocks-in-asia-open-lower-thursday-after-rough-day-on-wall-st/" data-title="Volatility Hits European and Asian Stocks After Frenzy on Wall Street" data-description="European markets fall as investors grow increasingly concerned over signs that global economic growth is faltering.">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="w480"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/16/business/17markets-01/17markets-01-blog480.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/16/business/17markets-01/17markets-01-blog480.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/16/business/17markets-01/17markets-01-blog480.jpg" id="100000003179290" width="480" height="304" alt="Visitors looking at a stock quotation board at the Tokyo Stock Exchange on Thursday."   /><meta itemprop="height" content="304"><meta itemprop="width" content="480"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Visitors looking at a stock quotation board at the Tokyo Stock Exchange on Thursday.</span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Yuya Shino/Reuters</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span id="t8h3s" class="update">Updated, 9:47 a.m. | </span>Global markets were again volatile on Thursday, as major stock market indexes in Europe turned sharply lower after a brief morning rebound.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In afternoon trading, stocks in London were down 1.7 percent, while stocks in Frankfurt were down 1.6 percent. Southern European markets were rockier: Spanish stocks were down 3.7 percent, and Italian shares were down 3.4 percent. Stocks in Tokyo closed down 2.2 percent.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Stocks tumbled in Europe and the United States on Wednesday as global investors fretted about signs that the worldâs major economies were faltering. The United States market recovered in afternoon trading.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;What we&#8217;ve seen over the last couple of days shows the level of nervousness that has been around for some time,&#8221; said Keith Bowman, an equity analyst at Hargreaves Lansdown in London, who added that investors continue to worry about a reduction of government support for local economies. &#8220;There&#8217;s a lot of questions about the global economy.&#8221;</p>
			<div class="nyt-article-promo">
								<div class="w190">
					<a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/10/16/u-s-stocks-open-lower/?ref=dealbook"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/17/business/Markets/Markets-thumbWide-v2.jpg" width="190" height="126" alt="Calm Returns to Wall St., but Europe Remains a Worry" /></a>
				</div>
                				<h4><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/10/16/u-s-stocks-open-lower/?ref=dealbook">Calm Returns to Wall St., but Europe Remains a Worry</a></h4>
				<p class="nyt-article-byline">By PETER EAVIS</p>
				<p class="nyt-article-summary">The United States market ended virtually flat on Thursday, after recovering from early losses â a steadying that came as a relief after a tumultuous day on world markets on Wednesday.</p>
			</div>
			
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The euro fell against major currencies on Thursday morning, trading at $1.2527. The British pound rose less than 1 percent against the dollar, making a pound worth $1.60.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A barrel of Brent crude oil, a global benchmark, lost more than $1, falling to $82.73 on Thursday, down from about $115 a barrel since its high in June. The drop is <a title="Previous coverage." href="//www.nytimes.com/2014/10/16/world/europe/fall-in-oil-prices-poses-a-problem-for-russia-iraq-and-others.html?ref=world">putting pressure on the budgets</a> of major petroleum-exporting countries. In addition, a barrel of the American benchmark, West Texas intermediate crude, was also trading lower, down $1.87. That pushed its price below $80 a barrel.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;The recent drop has come as a surprise to many because there is no apparent economic crisis to link it to,&#8221; Bank of America Merrill Lynch analysts told investors in a research note. &#8220;Oil prices have come off very sharply in recent weeks and are now back to levels last observed in 2010.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âThe fall in European stocks followed continuing weakness in Asia, where the Nikkei 225-share index in Japan fell as much as 2.6 percent on Thursday morning and closed 2.2 percent lower.</p>
		<div class="w190 right">
		<img src="//markets.on.nytimes.com/research/tools/builder/api.asp" width="190" height="250" alt=""/>		</div>
		<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">		<div class="w190 right">
		<img src="//markets.on.nytimes.com/research/tools/builder/api.asp" width="190" height="250" alt=""/>		</div>
				<div class="w190 right">
		<img src="//markets.on.nytimes.com/research/tools/builder/api.asp" width="190" height="250" alt=""/>		</div>
				<div class="w190 right">
		<img src="//markets.on.nytimes.com/research/tools/builder/api.asp" width="190" height="250" alt=""/>		</div>
		</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Australiaâs main index, the S.&amp;P./ASX 200, fell around 1 percent in the morning but recovered to positive territory, up 0.2 percent, in the afternoon. The Hang Seng index in Hong Kong was down 1 percent at the close.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Investors have grown increasingly concerned that policy makers may lack the monetary and fiscal tools necessary to stop the slide. Those fears tend to focus on the situation in Europe, where shares fell sharply on Wednesday. The FTSE 100 has fallen 10 percent since early September, while the German DAX and French CAC indexes have both fallen around 12 percent over the same time period.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">After longstanding efforts to jump-start the European economy, policy makers have again found themselves struggling to bolster growth.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Fears are growing that the eurozone is in the midst of a slow-motion descent toward another recession as inflation sits at a five-year low. Many economists warn that the eurozone economy is in danger of officially tipping into deflation, which can cause consumers to delay making purchases, companies to lose revenue and unemployment to soar from already high levels.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Eurostat, the European Unionâs statistics office, on Thursday confirmed its earlier estimate that inflation in the eurozone declined to an annualized rate of 0.3 percent in September from 0.4 percent in August, well below the European Central Bank&#8217;s target of just below 2 percent.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Slumping business activity, weak consumer spending and pared-back growth projections have started to take their toll, even in some of Europeâs largest economies like Germany and France.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8220;Investors are cautious,&#8221; Guy Foster, chief strategist at Brewin Dolphin in London, said in a research note to investors. &#8220;The eurozone needs both stimulus and reform, but is running out of time in the current political cycle in which to enact the reform.&#8221;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In Asia, concerns are focused on what policy makers in Japan can do to address declining growth. The rally that was set off by the stimulus measures introduced in early 2013 by Prime Minister Shinzo Abe appears largely to have fizzled in recent months, and a sales tax increase introduced in April has dragged down consumer spending. The Japanese economy shrank by an annualized 7.1 percent in the second quarter after the tax increase.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Investors are also concerned about slowing growth in China. Beijing in recent months has sought to address the slowdown through a number of narrowly targeted stimulus measures aimed, for example, at increasing the availability of financing for agriculture and subsidized housing. Despite the steps, the economy appears to still be cooling. China also pushed this year to weaken its currency, the renminbi â a move that tends to benefit exporters.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Mark Scott reported from London, and Neil Gough from Hong Kong. Liz Alderman contributed reporting from Paris, and James Kanter from Brussels.</em></p>
			<div class="nyt-article-promo">
								<div class="w190">
					<a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/10/15/stocks-tumble-on-global-growth-worries/?ref=dealbook"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2014/10/15/business/dbpix-markets7/dbpix-markets7-thumbWide-v2.jpg" width="190" height="126" alt="Steep Sell-Off Spreads Fear to Wall Street" /></a>
				</div>
                				<h4><a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2014/10/15/stocks-tumble-on-global-growth-worries/?ref=dealbook">Steep Sell-Off Spreads Fear to Wall Street</a></h4>
				<p class="nyt-article-byline">By PETER EAVIS and LANDON THOMAS JR.</p>
				<p class="nyt-article-summary">Dizzied by the turmoil, Wall Street experts agreed on one thing: The jarring day showed that fear had finally returned to markets that had become disconcertingly complacent.</p>
			</div>
			
	</div>
